    "The only way to solve c3 is to make a number of calls to the oracle which is equal to the number of possible action plans (with a maximum of two actions).",
    "This number will grow triangularly (n(n+1)",
    "2)-i.e., half of a square-with the number of actions. 30 This tractable",
    "(1) 28 To show this result in an algorithmic procedure, we can simply extend the exhaustive search (Algorithm 1) to iterate n actions over i values, e.g., by adding one additional for-loop for each i, or as a nested loop over values 1 to i within the loop over actions 1 to n. 29 See Lindner et al. (2020) for a similar analysis of action plans based on the SAS + formalism.",
    "30 As the famous story goes, Carl Friedrich Gauss quickly identified the formula for this series at a young age when asked by his teacher to add all the numbers between 1 and 100."
  ],
